</div><div class="info-panel__citations info-panel__item"><a href="#tab-citations" class="btn btn--inverse btn--slim" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="View Citations" aria-label="View Citations"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-format_quote"></i></a></div><div class="info-panel__formats info-panel__item"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="Go to purchase options" aria-label="Go to purchase options"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="link-text">Get Access</span></a></div></div></div></div></header><div data-core-nav="header" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-nav-wrapper core-container" aria-label="Article navigation"><div><button aria-controls="article_sections_menu" aria-expanded="false" aria-label="Toggle section navigation menu"><i class="icon-list" aria-hidden="true"></i><span>Contents</span></button><nav id="article_sections_menu" aria-label="Contents" data-core-nav="article"><ul><li><a href="#abstract">Abstract</a></li><li><a href="#core-sec-figures">Figures</a></li><li><a href="#bibliography">References</a></li></ul></nav></div><nav id="article_collateral_menu"><ul class="collateral-pill" data-core-nav="collateral"><li><a href="#core-collateral-info" aria-controls="core-collateral-info" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Information & Authors" title="Information & Authors" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-info"></i><span class="sr-only">Information & Authors</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-metrics" aria-controls="core-collateral-metrics" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Metrics & Citations" title="Metrics & Citations" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-metrics"></i><span class="sr-only">Metrics & Citations</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-controls="core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Get Access" title="Get Access" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="sr-only">Get Access</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-references" aria-controls="core-collateral-references" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="References" title="References" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-references"></i><span class="sr-only">References</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-figures" aria-controls="core-collateral-figures" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Figures" title="Figures" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-photo"></i><span class="sr-only">Figures</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-tables" aria-controls="core-collateral-tables" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Tables" title="Tables" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-table"></i><span class="sr-only">Tables</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-media" aria-controls="core-collateral-media" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Media" title="Media" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-play-circle-filled"></i><span class="sr-only">Media</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-share" aria-controls="core-collateral-share" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Share" title="Share" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-share"></i><span class="sr-only">Share</span></a></li></ul></nav></div></div><div data-core-wrapper="content"><div id="abstracts" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="abstract" property="abstract" typeof="Text" role="doc-abstract"><h2 property="name">Abstract</h2><div role="paragraph">Cystic fibrosis (CF) is the most common lethal autosomal recessive disease in the white population. Mutation of the CF transmembrane conductance regulator gene on chromosome 7 results in production of abnormally viscous mucus and secretions in the lungs of patients with CF. A similar pathologic process occurs in the gastrointestinal tract, pancreas, and hepatobiliary system. Inspissated mucus causes luminal obstruction and resultant clinical and radiologic complications associated with the disease process. Pancreatic involvement can result in exocrine and endocrine insufficiency, pancreatic atrophy, fatty replacement, or lipomatous pseudohypertrophy. Acute and chronic pancreatitis, pancreatic calcification, cysts, and cystosis also occur. Hepatic manifestations include hepatic steatosis, focal biliary and multilobular cirrhosis, and portal hypertension. Biliary complications include cholelithiasis, microgallbladder, and sclerosing cholangitis. The entire digestive tract can be involved. Distal ileal obstruction syndrome, intussusception, appendicitis, chronic constipation, colonic wall thickening, fibrosing colonopathy, pneumatosis intestinalis, gastroesophageal reflux, and peptic ulcer disease have been described. Renal manifestations include nephrolithiasis and secondary amyloidosis. The educational objectives of this review are to reveal the abdominal manifestations of CF to facilitate focused analysis of cross-sectional imaging in adult patients. Life expectancy in patients with CF continues to improve because of a combination of aggressive antibiotic treatment, improved emphasis on nutrition and physiotherapy, and development of promising new CF transmembrane conductance regulator modulators. As lung function and survival improve, extrapulmonary conditions, including hepatic and gastrointestinal malignancy, will be an increasing cause of morbidity and mortality. Awareness of the expected abdominal manifestations of CF may assist radiologists in identifying acute inflammatory or neoplastic conditions.</div><div role="paragraph"><sup>©</sup>RSNA, 2015</div></section></div></div><section id="bodymatter" data-extent="bodymatter" property="articleBody" typeof="Text"><div class="core-container"><section aria-labelledby="denial-block-title" class="denial-block "><h2 id="denial-block-title" class="denial-block__title">Get full access to this article</h2><p class="denial-block__text">View all available purchase options and get full access to this article.</p><div class="denial-block__cta"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span>Get Access</span></a></div><footer class="denial-block__footer"><span>Already a Subscriber? </span><span>Sign in as an </span><a href="/action/showLogin?redirectUri=/doi/10.1148/rg.2015140110">individual</a><span> or via your </span><a href="/action/ssostart?uri=/doi/10.1148/rg.2015140110">institution</a></footer></section></div></section><section id="backmatter" data-extent="backmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="core-sec-figures" data-type="figures"><h2>Figures</h2><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2015140110/asset/images/large/rg.2015140110.fig1a.jpeg" height="672" width="938" aria-labelledby="fig1a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1a</span> Fatty infiltration of the pancreas in a 34-year-old woman with <abbr title="cystic fibrosis">CF</abbr>. <b>(a)</b> Ultrasonographic (US) image shows a hyperechoic pancreas. <b>(b)</b> Corresponding portal venous phase computed tomographic (CT) scan shows complete fatty replacement of the pancreas and cirrhosis, with findings indicative of portal hypertension. <b>(c)</b> Axial T1-weighted magnetic resonance (MR) image in another patient with <abbr title="cystic fibrosis">CF</abbr> shows hyperintensity of the pancreas (arrows), which is isointense to subcutaneous fat.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2015140110&amp;id=fig1a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2015140110/asset/images/large/rg.2015140110.fig1b.jpeg" height="709" width="944" aria-labelledby="fig1b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1b</span> Fatty infiltration of the pancreas in a 34-year-old woman with <abbr title="cystic fibrosis">CF</abbr>. <b>(a)</b> Ultrasonographic (US) image shows a hyperechoic pancreas. <b>(b)</b> Corresponding portal venous phase computed tomographic (CT) scan shows complete fatty replacement of the pancreas and cirrhosis, with findings indicative of portal hypertension. <b>(c)</b> Axial T1-weighted magnetic resonance (MR) image in another patient with <abbr title="cystic fibrosis">CF</abbr> shows hyperintensity of the pancreas (arrows), which is isointense to subcutaneous fat.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2015140110&amp;id=fig1b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2015140110/asset/images/large/rg.2015140110.fig1c.jpeg" height="709" width="931" aria-labelledby="fig1c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1c</span> Fatty infiltration of the pancreas in a 34-year-old woman with <abbr title="cystic fibrosis">CF</abbr>. <b>(a)</b> Ultrasonographic (US) image shows a hyperechoic pancreas. <b>(b)</b> Corresponding portal venous phase computed tomographic (CT) scan shows complete fatty replacement of the pancreas and cirrhosis, with findings indicative of portal hypertension. <b>(c)</b> Axial T1-weighted magnetic resonance (MR) image in another patient with <abbr title="cystic fibrosis">CF</abbr> shows hyperintensity of the pancreas (arrows), which is isointense to subcutaneous fat.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2015140110&amp;id=fig1c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2015140110/asset/images/large/rg.2015140110.fig2.jpeg" height="641" width="900" aria-labelledby="fig2" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2</span> Axial portal venous phase CT scan in a 29-year-old man with <abbr title="cystic fibrosis">CF</abbr> shows diffuse atrophy of the pancreas.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2015140110&amp;id=fig2">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2015140110/asset/images/large/rg.2015140110.fig3.jpeg" height="708" width="900" aria-labelledby="fig3" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3</span> Preserved exocrine function in a 24-year-old man with <abbr title="cystic fibrosis">CF</abbr>. Axial portal venous phase CT scan shows peripancreatic fat stranding consistent with acute pancreatitis. Atrophy of the pancreas is also visible.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2015140110&amp;id=fig3">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2015140110/asset/images/large/rg.2015140110.fig4.jpeg" height="680" width="900" aria-labelledby="fig4" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4</span> Axial nonenhanced abdominal CT scan in a 28-year-old man with <abbr title="cystic fibrosis">CF</abbr> shows extensive pancreatic calcification. Severe pancreatic atrophy is also present.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2015140110&amp;id=fig4">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2015140110/asset/images/large/rg.2015140110.fig5a.jpeg" height="699" width="938" aria-labelledby="fig5a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5a</span> Pancreatic cysts in a 27-year-old woman with <abbr title="cystic fibrosis">CF</abbr>. Color Doppler US <b>(a)</b>, axial portal venous phase CT <b>(b)</b>, and T2-weighted MR <b>(c)</b> images show cysts in the head of the pancreas (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2015140110&amp;id=fig5a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2015140110/asset/images/large/rg.2015140110.fig5b.jpeg" height="696" width="938" aria-labelledby="fig5b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5b</span> Pancreatic cysts in a 27-year-old woman with <abbr title="cystic fibrosis">CF</abbr>. Color Doppler US <b>(a)</b>, axial portal venous phase CT <b>(b)</b>, and T2-weighted MR <b>(c)</b> images show cysts in the head of the pancreas (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2015140110&amp;id=fig5b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2015140110/asset/images/large/rg.2015140110.fig5c.jpeg" height="696" width="938" aria-labelledby="fig5c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5c</span> Pancreatic cysts in a 27-year-old woman with <abbr title="cystic fibrosis">CF</abbr>. Color Doppler US <b>(a)</b>, axial portal venous phase CT <b>(b)</b>, and T2-weighted MR <b>(c)</b> images show cysts in the head of the pancreas (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2015140110&amp;id=fig5c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2015140110/asset/images/large/rg.2015140110.fig6a.jpeg" height="690" width="948" aria-labelledby="fig6a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6a</span> Pancreatic cystosis. <b>(a)</b> Axial T2-weighted half-Fourier rapid acquisition with relaxation enhancement MR image in a 21-year-old woman with <abbr title="cystic fibrosis">CF</abbr> shows complete cystic replacement of the pancreas, a finding compatible with pancreatic cystosis. <b>(b)</b> Axial portal venous phase CT scan in a 29-year-old man with <abbr title="cystic fibrosis">CF</abbr> shows pancreatic cystosis. Fatty infiltration of the liver is also present.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2015140110&amp;id=fig6a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2015140110/asset/images/large/rg.2015140110.fig6b.jpeg" height="690" width="926" aria-labelledby="fig6b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6b</span> Pancreatic cystosis. <b>(a)</b> Axial T2-weighted half-Fourier rapid acquisition with relaxation enhancement MR image in a 21-year-old woman with <abbr title="cystic fibrosis">CF</abbr> shows complete cystic replacement of the pancreas, a finding compatible with pancreatic cystosis. <b>(b)</b> Axial portal venous phase CT scan in a 29-year-old man with <abbr title="cystic fibrosis">CF</abbr> shows pancreatic cystosis. Fatty infiltration of the liver is also present.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2015140110&amp;id=fig6b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2015140110/asset/images/large/rg.2015140110.fig7.jpeg" height="679" width="900" aria-labelledby="fig7" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7</span> Hepatic steatosis in a 19-year-old man with <abbr title="cystic fibrosis">CF</abbr>. US image of the liver shows increased echogenicity and poor visibility of vein walls.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2015140110&amp;id=fig7">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2015140110/asset/images/large/rg.2015140110.fig8a.jpeg" height="652" width="969" aria-labelledby="fig8a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8a</span> Focal biliary cirrhosis in a 23-year-old man with <abbr title="cystic fibrosis">CF</abbr>. US images of the right <b>(a)</b> and left <b>(b)</b> hepatic lobes show thickened echogenic periportal tissue, a finding indicative of focal biliary cirrhosis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2015140110&amp;id=fig8a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2015140110/asset/images/large/rg.2015140110.fig8b.jpeg" height="652" width="906" aria-labelledby="fig8b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8b</span> Focal biliary cirrhosis in a 23-year-old man with <abbr title="cystic fibrosis">CF</abbr>. US images of the right <b>(a)</b> and left <b>(b)</b> hepatic lobes show thickened echogenic periportal tissue, a finding indicative of focal biliary cirrhosis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2015140110&amp;id=fig8b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2015140110/asset/images/large/rg.2015140110.fig9a.jpeg" height="732" width="873" aria-labelledby="fig9a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9a</span> Severe <abbr title="cystic fibrosis">CF</abbr>-related liver disease requiring transplantation in a 19-year-old man with <abbr title="cystic fibrosis">CF</abbr>. <b>(a)</b> Axial portal venous phase CT scan shows multilobular cirrhosis, ascites, and splenic varices. <b>(b)</b> Intact liver explant specimen shows established macronodular cirrhosis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2015140110&amp;id=fig9a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2015140110/asset/images/large/rg.2015140110.fig9b.jpeg" height="732" width="1002" aria-labelledby="fig9b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9b</span> Severe <abbr title="cystic fibrosis">CF</abbr>-related liver disease requiring transplantation in a 19-year-old man with <abbr title="cystic fibrosis">CF</abbr>. <b>(a)</b> Axial portal venous phase CT scan shows multilobular cirrhosis, ascites, and splenic varices. <b>(b)</b> Intact liver explant specimen shows established macronodular cirrhosis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2015140110&amp;id=fig9b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2015140110/asset/images/large/rg.2015140110.fig10.jpeg" height="731" width="850" aria-labelledby="fig10" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10</span> Complications of portal hypertension in a 23-year-old man with <abbr title="cystic fibrosis">CF</abbr>. Coronal portal venous phase CT scan shows features of portal hypertension (distal esophageal and splenic varices, splenomegaly) requiring creation of a transjugular intrahepatic portosystemic shunt.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2015140110&amp;id=fig10">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2015140110/asset/images/large/rg.2015140110.fig11a.jpeg" height="722" width="900" aria-labelledby="fig11a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11a</span> Cirrhosis and a dysplastic nodule in a 23-year-old woman with <abbr title="cystic fibrosis">CF</abbr> who required transplantation for decompensated liver disease. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial T1-weighted <b>(a)</b> and T2-weighted <b>(b)</b> MR images show a cirrhotic liver with a nodule (arrow) that is 2 cm in diameter and is hyperintense in <b>a</b> and hypointense in <b>b</b>, findings suggestive of a dysplastic nodule. <b>(c)</b> Ventral aspect of intact liver explant specimen shows established cirrhosis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2015140110&amp;id=fig11a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2015140110/asset/images/large/rg.2015140110.fig11b.jpeg" height="671" width="864" aria-labelledby="fig11b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11b</span> Cirrhosis and a dysplastic nodule in a 23-year-old woman with <abbr title="cystic fibrosis">CF</abbr> who required transplantation for decompensated liver disease. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial T1-weighted <b>(a)</b> and T2-weighted <b>(b)</b> MR images show a cirrhotic liver with a nodule (arrow) that is 2 cm in diameter and is hyperintense in <b>a</b> and hypointense in <b>b</b>, findings suggestive of a dysplastic nodule. <b>(c)</b> Ventral aspect of intact liver explant specimen shows established cirrhosis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2015140110&amp;id=fig11b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2015140110/asset/images/large/rg.2015140110.fig11c.jpeg" height="671" width="1011" aria-labelledby="fig11c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11c</span> Cirrhosis and a dysplastic nodule in a 23-year-old woman with <abbr title="cystic fibrosis">CF</abbr> who required transplantation for decompensated liver disease. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial T1-weighted <b>(a)</b> and T2-weighted <b>(b)</b> MR images show a cirrhotic liver with a nodule (arrow) that is 2 cm in diameter and is hyperintense in <b>a</b> and hypointense in <b>b</b>, findings suggestive of a dysplastic nodule. <b>(c)</b> Ventral aspect of intact liver explant specimen shows established cirrhosis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2015140110&amp;id=fig11c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2015140110/asset/images/large/rg.2015140110.fig12a.jpeg" height="590" width="900" aria-labelledby="fig12a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12a</span> Cirrhosis in a 22-year-old man with <abbr title="cystic fibrosis">CF</abbr> who developed Barcelona Clinic Liver Cancer stage A <abbr title="hepatocellular carcinoma">HCC</abbr> and underwent liver transplantation. <b>(a)</b> US image shows a new 2.1-cm hypoechoic nodule (arrow). <b>(b, c)</b> Axial T1-weighted arterial phase <b>(b)</b> and delayed phase <b>(c)</b> MR images show a 2.4-cm solitary nodule (arrow) in a cirrhotic liver, with arterial enhancement in <b>b</b> and heterogeneous washout in <b>c</b>; the nodule was staged as a 5b lesion according to the Liver Imaging Reporting and Data System. <b>(d)</b> Section from the corresponding explant specimen, examination of which confirmed <abbr title="hepatocellular carcinoma">HCC</abbr> (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2015140110&amp;id=fig12a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2015140110/asset/images/large/rg.2015140110.fig12b.jpeg" height="887" width="698" aria-labelledby="fig12b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12b</span> Cirrhosis in a 22-year-old man with <abbr title="cystic fibrosis">CF</abbr> who developed Barcelona Clinic Liver Cancer stage A <abbr title="hepatocellular carcinoma">HCC</abbr> and underwent liver transplantation. <b>(a)</b> US image shows a new 2.1-cm hypoechoic nodule (arrow). <b>(b, c)</b> Axial T1-weighted arterial phase <b>(b)</b> and delayed phase <b>(c)</b> MR images show a 2.4-cm solitary nodule (arrow) in a cirrhotic liver, with arterial enhancement in <b>b</b> and heterogeneous washout in <b>c</b>; the nodule was staged as a 5b lesion according to the Liver Imaging Reporting and Data System. <b>(d)</b> Section from the corresponding explant specimen, examination of which confirmed <abbr title="hepatocellular carcinoma">HCC</abbr> (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2015140110&amp;id=fig12b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2015140110/asset/images/large/rg.2015140110.fig12c.jpeg" height="887" width="637" aria-labelledby="fig12c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12c</span> Cirrhosis in a 22-year-old man with <abbr title="cystic fibrosis">CF</abbr> who developed Barcelona Clinic Liver Cancer stage A <abbr title="hepatocellular carcinoma">HCC</abbr> and underwent liver transplantation. <b>(a)</b> US image shows a new 2.1-cm hypoechoic nodule (arrow). <b>(b, c)</b> Axial T1-weighted arterial phase <b>(b)</b> and delayed phase <b>(c)</b> MR images show a 2.4-cm solitary nodule (arrow) in a cirrhotic liver, with arterial enhancement in <b>b</b> and heterogeneous washout in <b>c</b>; the nodule was staged as a 5b lesion according to the Liver Imaging Reporting and Data System. <b>(d)</b> Section from the corresponding explant specimen, examination of which confirmed <abbr title="hepatocellular carcinoma">HCC</abbr> (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2015140110&amp;id=fig12c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2015140110/asset/images/large/rg.2015140110.fig12d.jpeg" height="887" width="516" aria-labelledby="fig12d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12d</span> Cirrhosis in a 22-year-old man with <abbr title="cystic fibrosis">CF</abbr> who developed Barcelona Clinic Liver Cancer stage A <abbr title="hepatocellular carcinoma">HCC</abbr> and underwent liver transplantation. <b>(a)</b> US image shows a new 2.1-cm hypoechoic nodule (arrow). <b>(b, c)</b> Axial T1-weighted arterial phase <b>(b)</b> and delayed phase <b>(c)</b> MR images show a 2.4-cm solitary nodule (arrow) in a cirrhotic liver, with arterial enhancement in <b>b</b> and heterogeneous washout in <b>c</b>; the nodule was staged as a 5b lesion according to the Liver Imaging Reporting and Data System. <b>(d)</b> Section from the corresponding explant specimen, examination of which confirmed <abbr title="hepatocellular carcinoma">HCC</abbr> (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2015140110&amp;id=fig12d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2015140110/asset/images/large/rg.2015140110.fig13a.jpeg" height="625" width="925" aria-labelledby="fig13a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13a</span> Microgallbladder in a 25-year-old woman with <abbr title="cystic fibrosis">CF</abbr>. <b>(a)</b> US image shows a microgallbladder (arrows). <b>(b)</b> Axial portal venous phase CT scan shows a microgallbladder (arrow) and cirrhotic liver.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2015140110&amp;id=fig13a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2015140110/asset/images/large/rg.2015140110.fig13b.jpeg" height="625" width="773" aria-labelledby="fig13b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13b</span> Microgallbladder in a 25-year-old woman with <abbr title="cystic fibrosis">CF</abbr>. <b>(a)</b> US image shows a microgallbladder (arrows). <b>(b)</b> Axial portal venous phase CT scan shows a microgallbladder (arrow) and cirrhotic liver.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2015140110&amp;id=fig13b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2015140110/asset/images/large/rg.2015140110.fig14a.jpeg" height="792" width="874" aria-labelledby="fig14a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14a</span> Intrahepatic ductal calculi in a 24-year-old man with <abbr title="cystic fibrosis">CF</abbr> who required a left lateral segmentectomy. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial true fast imaging with steady-state precession <b>(a)</b> and coronal maximum intensity projection <b>(b)</b> MR images show multiple gallbladder, intrahepatic, and extrahepatic calculi (arrows). <b>(c)</b> Corresponding endoscopic retrograde cholangiopancreatogram shows multiple filling defects attributable to choledocholithiasis and intrahepatic calculi (arrows). <b>(d)</b> Cut surface of resection specimen shows bile duct dilatation with inspissated bile and calculi.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2015140110&amp;id=fig14a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2015140110/asset/images/large/rg.2015140110.fig14b.jpeg" height="792" width="801" aria-labelledby="fig14b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14b</span> Intrahepatic ductal calculi in a 24-year-old man with <abbr title="cystic fibrosis">CF</abbr> who required a left lateral segmentectomy. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial true fast imaging with steady-state precession <b>(a)</b> and coronal maximum intensity projection <b>(b)</b> MR images show multiple gallbladder, intrahepatic, and extrahepatic calculi (arrows). <b>(c)</b> Corresponding endoscopic retrograde cholangiopancreatogram shows multiple filling defects attributable to choledocholithiasis and intrahepatic calculi (arrows). <b>(d)</b> Cut surface of resection specimen shows bile duct dilatation with inspissated bile and calculi.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2015140110&amp;id=fig14b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2015140110/asset/images/large/rg.2015140110.fig14c.jpeg" height="643" width="774" aria-labelledby="fig14c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14c</span> Intrahepatic ductal calculi in a 24-year-old man with <abbr title="cystic fibrosis">CF</abbr> who required a left lateral segmentectomy. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial true fast imaging with steady-state precession <b>(a)</b> and coronal maximum intensity projection <b>(b)</b> MR images show multiple gallbladder, intrahepatic, and extrahepatic calculi (arrows). <b>(c)</b> Corresponding endoscopic retrograde cholangiopancreatogram shows multiple filling defects attributable to choledocholithiasis and intrahepatic calculi (arrows). <b>(d)</b> Cut surface of resection specimen shows bile duct dilatation with inspissated bile and calculi.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2015140110&amp;id=fig14c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2015140110/asset/images/large/rg.2015140110.fig14d.jpeg" height="643" width="901" aria-labelledby="fig14d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14d</span> Intrahepatic ductal calculi in a 24-year-old man with <abbr title="cystic fibrosis">CF</abbr> who required a left lateral segmentectomy. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial true fast imaging with steady-state precession <b>(a)</b> and coronal maximum intensity projection <b>(b)</b> MR images show multiple gallbladder, intrahepatic, and extrahepatic calculi (arrows). <b>(c)</b> Corresponding endoscopic retrograde cholangiopancreatogram shows multiple filling defects attributable to choledocholithiasis and intrahepatic calculi (arrows). <b>(d)</b> Cut surface of resection specimen shows bile duct dilatation with inspissated bile and calculi.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2015140110&amp;id=fig14d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2015140110/asset/images/large/rg.2015140110.fig15a.jpeg" height="708" width="850" aria-labelledby="fig15a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15a</span> Sclerosing cholangitis equivalent in a 31-year-old man with <abbr title="cystic fibrosis">CF</abbr> who required left lateral segmentectomy because of recurrent infection. <b>(a, b)</b> Coronal maximum intensity projection MR image <b>(a)</b> and endoscopic retrograde cholangiopancreatogram <b>(b)</b> show intrahepatic ductal beading, dilatation, and stricturing in the left lobe of the liver (arrowhead). <b>(c)</b> Corresponding surgical specimen shows substantial intrahepatic bile duct dilatation with periductal fibrosis, luminal bile sludge, and small calculi.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2015140110&amp;id=fig15a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2015140110/asset/images/large/rg.2015140110.fig15b.jpeg" height="675" width="733" aria-labelledby="fig15b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15b</span> Sclerosing cholangitis equivalent in a 31-year-old man with <abbr title="cystic fibrosis">CF</abbr> who required left lateral segmentectomy because of recurrent infection. <b>(a, b)</b> Coronal maximum intensity projection MR image <b>(a)</b> and endoscopic retrograde cholangiopancreatogram <b>(b)</b> show intrahepatic ductal beading, dilatation, and stricturing in the left lobe of the liver (arrowhead). <b>(c)</b> Corresponding surgical specimen shows substantial intrahepatic bile duct dilatation with periductal fibrosis, luminal bile sludge, and small calculi.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2015140110&amp;id=fig15b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2015140110/asset/images/large/rg.2015140110.fig15c.jpeg" height="675" width="942" aria-labelledby="fig15c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15c</span> Sclerosing cholangitis equivalent in a 31-year-old man with <abbr title="cystic fibrosis">CF</abbr> who required left lateral segmentectomy because of recurrent infection. <b>(a, b)</b> Coronal maximum intensity projection MR image <b>(a)</b> and endoscopic retrograde cholangiopancreatogram <b>(b)</b> show intrahepatic ductal beading, dilatation, and stricturing in the left lobe of the liver (arrowhead). <b>(c)</b> Corresponding surgical specimen shows substantial intrahepatic bile duct dilatation with periductal fibrosis, luminal bile sludge, and small calculi.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2015140110&amp;id=fig15c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2015140110/asset/images/large/rg.2015140110.fig16a.jpeg" height="1046" width="800" aria-labelledby="fig16a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16a</span> <abbr title="distal ileal obstruction syndrome">DIOS</abbr>. <b>(a)</b> Coronal CT scan in a 26-year-old woman with <abbr title="cystic fibrosis">CF</abbr> shows small-bowel obstruction secondary to impacted fecal material (arrow) in the right lower quadrant. <b>(b)</b> Axial CT scan in another patient shows mucoid material (arrow) adherent to the small-bowel wall.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2015140110&amp;id=fig16a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2015140110/asset/images/large/rg.2015140110.fig16b.jpeg" height="716" width="876" aria-labelledby="fig16b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16b</span> <abbr title="distal ileal obstruction syndrome">DIOS</abbr>. <b>(a)</b> Coronal CT scan in a 26-year-old woman with <abbr title="cystic fibrosis">CF</abbr> shows small-bowel obstruction secondary to impacted fecal material (arrow) in the right lower quadrant. <b>(b)</b> Axial CT scan in another patient shows mucoid material (arrow) adherent to the small-bowel wall.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2015140110&amp;id=fig16b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig17" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2015140110/asset/images/large/rg.2015140110.fig17.jpeg" height="897" width="750" aria-labelledby="fig17" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 17</span> Severe gastroesophageal reflux disease in a 36-year-old woman with <abbr title="cystic fibrosis">CF</abbr>. Image from a barium swallow study shows severe reflux in the upper esophagus. Note the background bronchiectasis (arrows) and a right-sided peripherally inserted central venous catheter.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2015140110&amp;id=fig17">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig18" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2015140110/asset/images/large/rg.2015140110.fig18.jpeg" height="785" width="850" aria-labelledby="fig18" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 18</span> Intussusception in a 27-year-old man with <abbr title="cystic fibrosis">CF</abbr>. Axial CT scan shows transient asymptomatic intussusception (arrow) in a jejunal loop in the left upper quadrant.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2015140110&amp;id=fig18">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig19" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2015140110/asset/images/large/rg.2015140110.fig19.jpeg" height="680" width="730" aria-labelledby="fig19" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 19</span> Axial CT scan shows a thickened appendix in the right iliac fossa (arrow) but no adjacent inflammatory changes in a 34-year-old woman with <abbr title="cystic fibrosis">CF</abbr>. CT was performed to evaluate the liver for <abbr title="cystic fibrosis">CF</abbr>-related liver disease; the patient was asymptomatic and did not require intervention.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2015140110&amp;id=fig19">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig20" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2015140110/asset/images/large/rg.2015140110.fig20.jpeg" height="680" width="945" aria-labelledby="fig20" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 20</span> Appendiceal abscess in a 25-year-old man. Axial portal venous phase CT scan shows an appendiceal abscess (arrow) and adjacent fat stranding in the right iliac fossa.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2015140110&amp;id=fig20">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig21a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2015140110/asset/images/large/rg.2015140110.fig21a.jpeg" height="724" width="849" aria-labelledby="fig21a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 21a</span> Colonic wall redundancy in a 32-year-old woman with <abbr title="cystic fibrosis">CF</abbr>. Axial <b>(a)</b> and coronal <b>(b)</b> portal venous phase CT images show overlapping colonic folds causing a “double wrinkled” appearance (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2015140110&amp;id=fig21a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig21b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2015140110/asset/images/large/rg.2015140110.fig21b.jpeg" height="724" width="826" aria-labelledby="fig21b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 21b</span> Colonic wall redundancy in a 32-year-old woman with <abbr title="cystic fibrosis">CF</abbr>. Axial <b>(a)</b> and coronal <b>(b)</b> portal venous phase CT images show overlapping colonic folds causing a “double wrinkled” appearance (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2015140110&amp;id=fig21b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig22" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2015140110/asset/images/large/rg.2015140110.fig22.jpeg" height="850" width="767" aria-labelledby="fig22" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 22</span> Left-sided obstructing calculus in a 32-year-old woman with <abbr title="cystic fibrosis">CF</abbr>. Coronal nonenhanced CT image shows left-sided hydronephrosis attributable to an 8-mm obstructing calculus (arrow) at the pelviureteric junction. The patient also had a right-sided ureteric stent in situ (arrowhead).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2015140110&amp;id=fig22">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig23a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2015140110/asset/images/large/rg.2015140110.fig23a.jpeg" height="764" width="832" aria-labelledby="fig23a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 23a</span> Amyloidosis at renal biopsy in a 29-year-old man with <abbr title="cystic fibrosis">CF</abbr>. <b>(a)</b> US image shows an enlarged right kidney. <b>(b)</b> Microscopic slide with Congo red staining shows bright red stain in glomeruli and vessels, consistent with amyloid deposition, which was confirmed under polarized light.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2015140110&amp;id=fig23a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig23b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2015140110/asset/images/large/rg.2015140110.fig23b.jpeg" height="764" width="842" aria-labelledby="fig23b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 23b</span> Amyloidosis at renal biopsy in a 29-year-old man with <abbr title="cystic fibrosis">CF</abbr>. <b>(a)</b> US image shows an enlarged right kidney. <b>(b)</b> Microscopic slide with Congo red staining shows bright red stain in glomeruli and vessels, consistent with amyloid deposition, which was confirmed under polarized light.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2015140110&amp;id=fig23b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div></section><section id="bibliography" role="doc-bibliography"><h2>References</h2><div role="list"><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">1.</div><div id="r1" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Cystic Fibrosis Foundation. Patient Registry 2012. Bethesda, MD: Cystic Fibrosis Foundation, 2013; 1–32.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?title=Cystic+Fibrosis+Foundation.+Patient+Registry+2012&amp;publication_year=2013&amp;pages=1-32">Google Scholar</a></div></div></div></div></div><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">2.</div><div id="r2" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Farrell PM. The prevalence of cystic fibrosis in the European Union. <em>J Cyst Fibros</em> 2008;7(5):450–453.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.jcf.2008.03.007">Crossref</a></div><div class="core-xlink-pubmed"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/18442953/">PubMed</a></div><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?title=The+prevalence+of+cystic+fibrosis+in+the+European+Union&amp;author=PM+Fa